##For the first time, Hong Kong Harbour city is cutting its rents by half

Hong Kong's biggest high-end shopping mall, Harbour City, Asia's most lucrative mall, is also cutting rents in the wake of the epidemic.

On February 12, several Hong Kong media reported that an internal e-mail from harbour city to its tenants showed that the new pneumonia outbreak had caused a sharp drop in shopping mall traffic and severely affected the performance of several brands. To ease the pressure on businesses, harbour city has decided to halve rents for February. The city did not disclose details of the negotiations or contractual arrangements because of confidentiality terms with the tenants.

As of 19:55 a.m. on Feb. 13, there were 51 confirmed cases of COVID-19 pneumonia in Hong Kong, according to the National Institutes of health.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Harbour city is one of the hallmarks of Hong Kong's retail industry. In the 10 years since 2007, the combined annual growth rate of the city's sales has been more than 10% , and 24% in 2018, benefiting from a shopping boom by mainland tourists.

In 2018, the city's sales exceeded HK $37 billion, or an average of over HK $100 million per day. In the first half of 2019, revenue still rose 5 PER CENT TO HK $6.156 BN, while the occupancy rate remained at 96 per cent.

At present, there are many shops in the harbour city closed for business, including more than 24 boarded-up facade.

A Hong Kong user named "Patrick the Reporter" posted a picture of the port city on Twitter with the caption "port city on a weekday afternoon, 2020.02.06. " The entrance to the once-crowded port city is now empty.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Harbour city, taken by a netizen.

"people are deliberately cutting down on the amount of partying they go out to, but commuters still need to take public transport, and many of the stops they have to go through are set up downstairs, which is inevitable, but shopping is OK, " Hugo Wong, who works near Tsim Sha Tsui in Hong Kong, told interface news. Although all Hong Kong residents have donned face masks, the flow of people on the streets has not decreased significantly.

But Hong Kong's largest consumer of luxury goods retail is from the mainland. In response to the outbreak, the Hong Kong government has stepped up its control on entry and exit since February 4,2020, and the number of visitors to Hong Kong has fallen to a record low.

With the impact of 2019 still undigested and the onset of new pneumonia, the purchasing power of today may not be sufficient to sustain their past glories.

Harbour City's parent company is wharf properties, which also owns five properties, including Times Square, Plaza Hollywood and central. There is no other information on rent reduction. But before new crown pneumonia broke out, Louis Vuitton, one of the world's largest luxury brands, was planning to close its second-floor Times Square store after its owner, The Wharf (Holdings) Limited properties, refused to cut rents.

Hong Kong's cosmetics and jewellery industry has also been overshadowed by the outbreak of new crown pneumonia, which is affecting not only luxury goods but also the city's cosmetics and jewellery industry.

Sasa has announced that 21 of its Hong Kong and Macau stores have closed temporarily; Chow Tai Fook Enterprises said that more than 40 stores in Hong Kong and Macau have closed, while the rest have reduced their opening hours; and Tse Sui Luen has announced on social media platforms that, more than half of its stores in Hong Kong have been closed.

Hong Kong remains one of the few retail outlets to be closed, but the industry is no longer sanguine.

Average business volumes at most Hong Kong retailers fell by as much as 50 per cent during the 10-day Lunar New Year holiday from January 24 as the retail industry entered the "super cold winter" , according to a survey released by the Hong Kong Retail Management Association on Thursday. With the new coronavirus epidemic raging, members expect business to fall 40% to 60% between February and march.

The retail winter has made Hong Kong's people decide to help each other.

On February 11, the Real Estate Developers Association of Hong Kong (Reda) issued a statement stating that in view of the current difficult situation in the retail and catering industry, its members will continue to explore with tenants in need on a case-by-case basis all possible options, these include measures such as rent concessions to relieve their operating pressure.

Sun Hung Kai Properties, New World Development, hang lung properties and swire properties have responded by offering rent relief or promising to step up their promotion efforts to tide over the difficult times. The waiver will cover major shopping centres in Hong Kong, such as the International Finance Centre shopping centre, APM, K11 and Pacific Place Shopping Centre.

But rent relief may be a drop in the bucket for Hong Kong's retail sector, which has been rocked by social unrest for much of last year and worsened by the pneumonia epidemic.
